{
  "texts": [
    "Capability innovation requires open-source contributors to conceptualize features without predetermined specifications, demanding substantial human input to conceptualize and execute novel approaches that lack precedent within the project context.",
    "In contrast, iterative innovation focuses on refining existing project elements to function better, where cognitive efforts need to be focused on finding the correct solution within the established parameters.",
    "Iterative innovation on open-source starts with understanding existing code-often written by others-before making targeted improvements that navigate complex codebase interdependencies (Medappa and Srivastava 2019).",
    "Iterative innovation can happen with limited human input-the existing work itself forms part of the input along with the type of improvement needed.",
    "Figure 1 Understanding how LLMs affect these distinct innovation types is particularly important in collaborative settings, which benefit from greater knowledge diversity but face coordination challenges, making them rife for technology augmentation using LLMs."
  ]
}